<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,592,331,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Stratigraphy and Geological age:</emphasis>
Katipiri Formation; mid- to late Pleistocene; the fossils are assumed to have derived from fluvial sediments that outcrop in the banks of the river at this point. The associated fauna comprises the Kalamurina Fauna and is typical of the late Pleistocene (
<bibRefCitation author="Tedford, R. H. &amp; Wells, R. T." box="[783,1037,403,429]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="263 - 284" refId="ref17570" refString="Tedford, R. H. &amp; Wells, R. T. (1990) Pleistocene deposits and fossil vertebrates from the &quot; dead heart of Australia &quot;. Memoirs of the Queensland Museum, 28 (1), 263 - 284." type="journal article" year="1990">Tedford &amp; Wells 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Tedford, R. H. &amp; Wells, R. T. &amp; Barghoorn, S. F." box="[1049,1265,403,430]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="173 - 194" refId="ref17615" refString="Tedford, R. H., Wells, R. T. &amp; Barghoorn, S. F. (1992) Tirari Formation and contained faunas, Pliocene of the Lake Eyre Basin, South Australia. Beagle: Records of the Museums and Art Galleries of the Northern Territory, 9 (1), 173 - 194. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / p. 263124" type="journal article" year="1992">Tedford et al. 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,626,439,465]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Measurements (mm) of QM F.5507:</emphasis>
preserved distal width 35.5, lateromedial width of the condylus dorsalis 9.1, depth of the condylus dorsalis 22.3, proximodistal length of the condylus dorsalis 12.3, width of the condylus ventralis 14.1.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,1185]" box="[199,599,547,574]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,441,547,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Amended diagnosis:</emphasis>
As for genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,223,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,583,609]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Description:</emphasis>
In addition to the diagnostic characters described above, the following characters serve to distinguish the species: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[360,393,619,645]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(8)</emphasis>
the palmar attachment for the m. extensor metacarpi radialis (
<figureCitation box="[1103,1258,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A, C</figureCitation>
; PEMR) on the cranial facies immediately ventral of the tuberculum supracondylare dorsale (
<figureCitation box="[1018,1136,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
; TSD), is shallow, roughly oval-shaped, and orientated dorsoventrally; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[641,674,691,717]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(9)</emphasis>
the sulcus for the dorsal attachment of the m. extensor metacarpi radialis (
<figureCitation box="[226,375,727,754]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A, B</figureCitation>
; DEMR) is large and deep on the dorsal facies of the tuberculum supracondylare dorsale, and is directed dorsoproximally; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[447,493,763,789]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(10)</emphasis>
the epicondylus dorsalis is dorsally flat and does not project dorsally of the condylus dorsalis; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[253,297,799,825]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(11)</emphasis>
the fossa m. brachialis (
<figureCitation box="[567,685,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
; FB) is deep, with the distal margin positioned well proximal to the tuberculum supracondylare ventrale; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[568,615,835,861]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(12)</emphasis>
the dorsal margin of the fossa m. brachialis extends close to (~ 
<quantity box="[1321,1387,835,861]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
) the dorsal margin of the shaft; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[457,504,871,897]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(13)</emphasis>
the tuberculum supracondylare ventrale (
<figureCitation box="[972,1091,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
; TSV) is not inflated ventrally and is moderately projected cranially; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[580,626,907,933]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(14)</emphasis>
the interior margin of the tuberculum supracondylare ventrale is aligned roughly parallel to the adjacent medial surface; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[684,731,943,969]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(15)</emphasis>
the attachment scars for the origin of the distal head of m. pronator superficialis and of m. pronator profundus are deep, with that for the former being deepest; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1251,1298,979,1005]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(16)</emphasis>
the incisura intercondylaris (
<figureCitation box="[333,451,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
; II) is relatively broad, roughly 
<quantity box="[805,870,1015,1042]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="3.0">3 mm</quantity>
in width, and distinctly separates the two condyles cranially; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,310,1051,1077]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(17)</emphasis>
the distal point of the condylus dorsalis (
<figureCitation box="[772,891,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
; CD) is set well proximal of the distalmost point of the condylus ventralis, with the distal margin forming a broad, shallow notch between the two condyles; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1349,1396,1087,1113]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(18)</emphasis>
the distoventral margin of the condylus ventralis (
<figureCitation box="[675,795,1123,1149]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1A</figureCitation>
; CV) is continuous with the entepicondyle; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1298,1344,1123,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">(19)</emphasis>
and the sulcus scapulotricipitalis (
<figureCitation box="[442,561,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[217,1356,194,1719]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[214,1373,181,1738]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 1. Comparisons of the distal humeri of Cryptogyps lacertosus QM F5507 (scanned, A, D, G), Aquila audax (B, E, H) and Haliaeetus leucogaster (C, F, I) in cranial (A, B, C), caudal (D, E, F) and ventral (G, H, I) view. Abbreviations: CD, condylus dorsalis; CV, condylus ventralis; DEMR, dorsal attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; ED, epicondylus dorsalis; EV, epicondylus ventralis; FB, fossa brachialis; FO, fossa olecrani; II, incisura intercondylaris; MeDCo, m. extensor digitorum communi origin; MPSO, origin of distal head of m. pronator superficialis; MPPO, m. pronator profundus origin; PF, processus flexorius; PEMR, palmar attachment m. extensor metacarpi radialis; SHTD, dorsal sulcus humerotricipitalis; SHTV, ventral sulcus humerotricipitalis; SST, sulcus scapulotricipitalis; TSD, tuberculum supracondylare dorsale; TSV, tuberculum supracondylare ventrale. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6876165" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6876165/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figure 1D</figureCitation>
; SST) is shallow and relatively broad.
